MEI.ext Ranks (created: 10 May 2011)

Bimonthly ranks of the MEI.ext, Dec1870/Jan1871 through Nov/Dec 2005, or 135 full years. If two MEI 
values are identical within the same bimonthly season, their rank is split between them, leading to
a ".5" value. 

How can one interpret these ranks?  Given that there are 135 numbers in each column, the lowest
number (1) would denote the strongest La Nina case for that bimonthly season, while the highest
number (135) would indicate the strongest El Nino case.  For instance, in December-January 
(DECJAN), the strongest La Nina was recorded in 1974, while the strongest El Nino occurred in 1983,
showing that the period since 1950 harbors the most extreme cases for that season.

If we use percentiles (say, 30%ile) to define La Nina, near-normal, and El Nino, MEI ranks from 1-41
denote weak to strong La Nina conditions, while 95-135 denote weak to strong El Nino conditions.
If one uses the quintile definition for (moderate or stronger) ENSO events, MEI ranks from 1-27
would denote La Nina, while 109-135 would denote El Nino.  Finally, the comparison figures on this
website refer to strong ENSO events, such as might be defined by the top 14 (one tenth or smaller)
ranks, such as 1-14 for La Nina, and 122-135 for El Nino. Actually, the comparison figures were
constructed using only cases between 1871-1949.
